{{Italic title}} [[File:DickBrewer BillytheKid Regulators1620 0910.jpg|thumb|''Dick Brewer, Billy the Kid and the Regulators'' by Andrew Thomas]]
'''''Dick Brewer, Billy the Kid and the Regulators''''' is a painting by artist Andrew "Andy" Thomas that depicts the [[Lincoln County Regulators|Regulators]] as they hunt down William Morton and Frank Baker for the murder of businessman [[John Tunstall]]. This painting was sold at the Midwest Gathering of Artists in [[Carthage, Missouri]] on September 11, 2010.<ref name="carthagepress" />
==Background== The event depicted in this painting by Andrew Thomas occurred during the [[Lincoln County War]]. [[Richard M. Brewer|Dick Brewer]], [[Billy the Kid]], and the other Regulators were given warrants for the murderers of Tunstall, which included William Morton. After a five-mile gun chase, Morton surrendered on the condition that he and Baker would not be killed. On the third day on the trip back to [[Lincoln, New Mexico|Lincoln]] however, Morton and Baker ended up dead. The Regulators said that the prisoners had tried to escape; the [[James Dolan (Lincoln County War)|Dolan]] forces believed that the Regulators had actually murdered Baker and Morton, but the only witnesses were the potential murderers themselves.<ref name="Utley" />
==Sources== {{Reflist |refs= <ref name="carthagepress">{{Cite web |url=http://www.carthagepress.com/entertainment/arts/x1870171638/Artist-Andy-Thomas-finds-local-link-to-Regulators-Billy-the-Kid |work=carthagepress.com |title=Artist Andy Thomas finds local link to Regulators, Billy the Kid |first=John |last=Hacker |date=September 10, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430142822/http://www.carthagepress.com/entertainment/arts/x1870171638/Artist-Andy-Thomas-finds-local-link-to-Regulators-Billy-the-Kid |archivedate=2011-04-30 |df= }}</ref> <ref name="Utley">{{Cite book |title=Billy the Kid: A Short and Violent Life |first=Robert M. |last=Utley |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |year=1989 |isbn=0-8032-9558-8 |pages=56–58}}</ref> }}
